# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: extinct-in-the-wild
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] The plant is native to tiny Pitcairn Island (3 by 2 km (1.9 by 1.2 mi)), a remote island between New Zealand and South America which is mostly known for being settled by the mutineers from HMS *Bounty*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] After being considered extinct for twenty years, a single plant was found growing in native forest of *Homalium taypau* and *Metrosideros collina* in 2003.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] Vegetative propagation, along with seed from the plant, were used to establish a small population on the island's nursery, with some propagation material also being sent to Trinity College Botanic Gardens, Dublin.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] A landslide killed the only wild plant in 2005, making the plant extinct in the wild.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] Cuttings from the Trinity College collection were taken to the National Botanic Gardens of Ireland, Glasnevin in 2007, and later to the Royal Botanical Gardens, Kew.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] The forest where the plant is native is threatened by invasive species, with the *Homalium taypau* trees under competition from *Syzygium jambos* and *Lantana camara*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] Chemical control of the invasive plants, along with reintroduction of native species, have had some success.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] In 2011, there were plans to attempt the reintroduction of *Abutilon pitcairnense* to the island.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] There are also plans for a more thorough search of the island for surviving native plants during July and August, the flowering season of *Abutilon pitcairnense*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/abutilon-pitcairnense] In 2018, it was reported that the Royal Botanical Gardens in Kew had stored seeds in the Millennium Seed Bank at Wakehurst and were working on propagating the plant.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The **Alagoas curassow** (***Mitu mitu***) is a glossy-black, pheasant-like bird.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] It was formerly found in forests in Northeastern Brazil in what is now the states of Pernambuco and Alagoas, which is the origin of its common name.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] It is now extinct in the wild; there are about 200 individuals in captivity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] German naturalist Georg Marcgrave first identified the Alagoas curassow in 1648 in its native range.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Subsequently, the origin and legitimacy of the bird began to be questioned due to the lack of specimens.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] An adult female curassow was rediscovered in 1951, in the coastal forests of Alagoas.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The *Pauxi mitu* was then accepted as a separate species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] At that time fewer than 60 birds were left in the wild, in the forests around São Miguel dos Campos.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Several authors in the 1970s brought to light the growing destruction of its habitat and the rarity of the species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Even with these concerns, the last large forest remnants which contained native Alagoas curassow were demolished for sugarcane agriculture.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The Alagoas curassow measures approximately 83–89 centimetres (33–35 in) in length.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Feathers covering its body are black and glossy, with a blue-purple hue.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Specimens of *Pauxi mitu* also has a large, bright red beak, flattened at its sides, with a white tip.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The same red coloration found on its legs and feet.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The tips of its tail feathers are light brown in color, with chestnut colored feathers under the tail.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] It has a unique grey colored, crescent-shaped patch of bare skin covering its ears, a character not found in other curassows.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The distinct coloration separates *P. mitu* as its own species distinct from other curassow species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Sexual dimorphism is not pronounced: females tend to be lighter in color and slightly smaller in size.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] In captivity, the birds can live to at least 24 years of age.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Video recording in captivity show that this cracid sporadically makes a high-pitched chirping sound.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Since 1977, the entire *Mitu mitu* population has been in captivity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The population numbered 44 in 2000, and by 2008, there were 130 birds in two aviaries.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] About 35% of the birds were hybrids with *M. tuberosum*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Due to their absence in the wild and lack of study previously conducted on these cracids before their extinction in the wild, not much is known about their breeding habits outside of captivity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Alagoas curassow females begin reproducing at about 2 years old.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] In captivity, they produce about 2–3 eggs each year.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] There has been a greater genetic variability amongst the Alagoas curassow after 1990, when hybrid breeding programs were introduced; Alagoas curassows were bred with closely related razor-billed curassows.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The Alagoas curassow was first mentioned by German naturalist Georg Marcgrave in his work *Historia Naturalis Brasiliae* which was published in 1648.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Because of the lack of information and specimens, it was considered conspecific with the common razor-billed curassow, until its rediscovery in 1951 in the Alagoas lowland forests, Brazil.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Phylogenetic analyses based on mitochondrial gene sequences indicate that *M. mitu* is sister to the crestless curassow, the other *Mitu* species with brown eumelanin in the tail tip; together, these two species are the sister group to the rest of the *Mitu* genus.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The Alagoas curassow lineage has been distinct since the Miocene-Pliocene boundary (approximately 5 million years ago), when it became isolated in refugia in the Atlantic Forest.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] As this species is extinct in the wild, the total population of 130 birds only persists in two separate captive populations.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] A reintroduction plan is being organized, though it faces challenges.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Even if the population could be bred to healthy numbers, the species would need to be reintroduced into a large natural geographical area.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Human expansion and overpopulation has caused nearly all of the Alagoas curassow's natural habitat to be destroyed.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] One potential reintroduction site has been proposed.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Precautions would have to be taken in order to prevent illegal hunting of the species after reintroduction.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The Alagoas curassow became extinct in the wild due to deforestation and hunting.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The last wild Alagoas curassow was seen and killed in 1984, or possibly 1987 or 1988.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The captive population has been extensively hybridized with the razor-billed curassow, and there are several dozen purebred birds left.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] These are being maintained and bred in two privately owned professional aviaries in Brazil mainly due to lack of official interest owing to the long-standing doubt about the taxon's validity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The Alagoas curassow is known to consume a diet of fruits and nuts.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Although not much information is known about this species' interactions and behavior in the wild, the stomach contents of these birds were found to contain fruits specifically from the castelo tree.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] It has also been said that they enjoy fruits from the plant *Clarisia racemosa*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Generally, the female birds weigh less than the males and lay about 2–3 eggs a year.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The average lifespan in captivity is about 24 years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The lack of knowledge about their behavior in the wild makes it difficult to know how the birds interact with other species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The impact of their introduction on interactions with other species is difficult to predict.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] For instance, the Chamek spider monkey also eats *Clarisia racemosa*, which could lead to competition with the Alagoas curassow.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] A lack of genetic diversity is another potential concern.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Scientists have been controlling the sexual interactions within the species by pairing certain birds together in order to reduce hybridization and maintain the original Alagoas curassow.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] With the objective to preserve the species and to increase genetic variability in the population, the "original" stock had their DNA examined by scientists in order to guide future pairings.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] Once a captive population has been successfully created, they can start being reintroduced back into the wild.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/alagoas-curassow] The more ideal locations would be large forest remnants, such as those located at Usina Utinga-Leão and Usina Serra Grande.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The term has been used in sophisticated research relating to Earth's water and salt, geology, geomorphology, landscape, limnology, hydrology, ecosystems and climate.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The effects of human activities on Earth can be seen, for example, in regards to biodiversity loss, and climate change.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Various start dates for the Anthropocene have been proposed, ranging from the beginning of the Neolithic Revolution (12,000–15,000 years ago), to as recently as the 1960s.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Stoermer is credited with first coining and using the term *anthropocene* informally in the 1980s; Paul J.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Crutzen re-invented and popularized the term.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The Anthropocene Working Group (AWG) of the Subcommission on Quaternary Stratigraphy (SQS) of the ICS voted in 2016 to proceed towards a formal golden spike (GSSP) proposal to define an Anthropocene epoch in the geologic time scale.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Later that year, the group presented the proposal to the International Geological Congress.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In 2019, the AWG voted in favour of submitting a formal proposal to the ICS by 2021.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The proposal located potential stratigraphic markers to the mid-20th century.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] This time period coincides with the start of the Great Acceleration, a post-World War II time period during which global population growth, economic growth, pollution and exploitation of natural resources have all increased at a dramatic rate.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The Atomic Age also started around the mid-20th century, when the risks of nuclear wars, nuclear terrorism, and nuclear accidents increased.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Twelve candidate sites were selected for the GSSP; the sediments of Crawford Lake (Halton Region), Canada were finally proposed, in 2023, to mark the lower boundary of the Anthropocene, starting with the Crawfordian stage/age in 1950.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In 2024, after 15 years of deliberation, the Anthropocene Epoch proposal of the AWG was voted down by a wide margin by the SQS, owing largely to its shallow sedimentary record and extremely recent proposed start date.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The ICS and the IUGS later formally confirmed, by a near unanimous vote, the rejection of the AWG's Anthropocene Epoch proposal for inclusion in the Geologic Time Scale.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] As early as 1873, the Italian geologist Antonio Stoppani acknowledged the increasing power and effect of humanity on the Earth's systems and referred to an 'anthropozoic era'.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] From 1877 onward, the term 'Psychozoic' was used by geologists such as Joseph LeConte and Johannes Herman Frederik Umbgrove.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] An early concept for the Anthropocene was the Noosphere by Vladimir Vernadsky, who in 1938 wrote of "scientific thought as a geological force".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Scientists in the Soviet Union appear to have used the term *Anthropocene* as early as the 1960s to refer to the Quaternary, the most recent geological period.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Stoermer subsequently used *Anthropocene* with a different sense in the 1980s and the term was widely popularised in 2000 by atmospheric chemist Paul J.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Crutzen, who regarded the influence of human behavior on Earth's atmosphere in recent centuries as so significant as to constitute a new geological epoch.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The term *Anthropocene* is informally used in scientific contexts.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The Geological Society of America entitled its 2011 annual meeting: *Archean to Anthropocene: The past is the key to the future*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The new epoch has no agreed start-date, but one proposal, based on atmospheric evidence, is to fix the start with the Industrial Revolution c.1780, with the invention of the steam engine.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Other scientists link the new term to earlier events, such as the rise of agriculture and the Neolithic Revolution (around 12,000 years BP).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Evidence of relative human impact – such as the growing human influence on land use, ecosystems, biodiversity, and species extinction – is substantial; scientists think that human impact has significantly changed (or halted) the growth of biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In 2008, the Stratigraphy Commission of the Geological Society of London considered a proposal to make the Anthropocene a formal unit of geological epoch divisions.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] A majority of the commission decided the proposal had merit and should be examined further.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Independent working groups of scientists from various geological societies began to determine whether the Anthropocene will be formally accepted into the Geological Time Scale.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In January 2015, 26 of the 38 members of the International Anthropocene Working Group published a paper suggesting the Trinity test on 16 July 1945 as the starting point of the proposed new epoch.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] However, a significant minority supported one of several alternative dates.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] A March 2015 report suggested either 1610 or 1964 as the beginning of the Anthropocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Other scholars pointed to the diachronous character of the physical strata of the Anthropocene, arguing that onset and impact are spread out over time, not reducible to a single instant or date of start.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] A January 2016 report on the climatic, biological, and geochemical signatures of human activity in sediments and ice cores suggested the era since the mid-20th century should be recognised as a geological epoch distinct from the Holocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The Anthropocene Working Group met in April 2016 to consolidate evidence supporting the argument for the *Anthropocene* as a true geologic epoch.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Evidence was evaluated and the group voted to recommend *Anthropocene* as the new geological epoch in August 2016.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In April 2019, the Anthropocene Working Group (AWG) announced that they would vote on a formal proposal to the International Commission on Stratigraphy, to continue the process started at the 2016 meeting.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In May 2019, 29 members of the 34 person AWG panel voted in favour of an official proposal to be made by 2021.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The AWG also voted with 29 votes in favour of a starting date in the mid 20th century.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Ten candidate sites for a Global boundary Stratotype Section and Point have been identified, one of which will be chosen to be included in the final proposal.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Possible markers include microplastics, heavy metals, or radioactive nuclei left by tests from thermonuclear weapons.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In November 2021, an alternative proposal that the Anthropocene is a geological event, not an epoch, was published and later expanded in 2022.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] This challenged the assumption underlying the case for the Anthropocene epoch – the idea that it is possible to accurately assign a precise date of start to highly diachronous processes of human-influenced Earth system change.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The argument indicated that finding a single GSSP would be impractical, given human-induced changes in the Earth system occurred at different periods, in different places, and spread under different rates.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The authors are members of the AWG who had voted against the official proposal of a starting date in the mid-20th century, and sought to reconcile some of the previous models (including Ruddiman and Maslin proposals).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] They cited Crutzen's original concept, arguing that the Anthropocene is much better and more usefully conceived of as an unfolding geological event, like other major transformations in Earth's history such as the Great Oxidation Event.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In July 2023, the AWG chose Crawford Lake in Ontario, Canada as a site representing the beginning of the proposed new epoch.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Had it been approved, the official declaration of the new Anthropocene epoch would have taken place in August 2024, and its first age may have been named **Crawfordian** after the lake.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In March 2024, an internal vote was held by the IUGS: After nearly 15 years of debate, the proposal to ratify the Anthropocene had been defeated by a 12-to-4 margin, with 2 abstentions.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] These results were not out of a dismissal of human impact on the planet, but rather an inability to constrain the Anthropocene in a geological context.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] This is because the widely-adopted 1950 start date was found to be prone to recency bias.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] It also overshadowed earlier examples of human impacts, many of which happened in different parts of the world at different times.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Although the proposal could be raised again, this would require the entire process of debate to start from the beginning.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The results of the vote were officially confirmed by the IUGS and upheld as definitive later that month.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Crutzen proposed the Industrial Revolution as the start of Anthropocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Lovelock proposes that the Anthropocene began with the first application of the Newcomen steam engine in 1712.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change takes the pre-industrial era (chosen as the year 1750) as the baseline related to changes in long-lived, well mixed greenhouse gases.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Although it is apparent that the Industrial Revolution ushered in an unprecedented global human impact on the planet, much of Earth's landscape already had been profoundly modified by human activities.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The human impact on Earth has grown progressively, with few substantial slowdowns.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] A 2024 scientific perspective paper authored by a group of scientists led by William J.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In May 2019 the twenty-nine members of the Anthropocene Working Group (AWG) proposed a start date for the Epoch in the mid-20th century, as that period saw "a rapidly rising human population accelerated the pace of industrial production, the use of agricultural chemicals and other human activities.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The peak in radionuclides fallout consequential to atomic bomb testing during the 1950s is another possible date for the beginning of the Anthropocene (the detonation of the first atomic bomb in 1945 or the Partial Nuclear Test Ban Treaty in 1963).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] On 19 June 2025, Vincent Gauci proposed that Anthropocene began in 1592.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Ice core records had shown a minimum atmospheric methane concentration at that time.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The name *Anthropocene* is a combination of *anthropo-* from the Ancient Greek ἄνθρωπος (*ánthropos*) meaning 'human' and *-cene* from καινός (*kainós*) meaning 'new' or 'recent'.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The human impact on biodiversity forms one of the primary attributes of the Anthropocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Humankind has entered what is sometimes called the Earth's sixth major extinction.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Most experts agree that human activities have accelerated the rate of species extinction.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The exact rate remains controversial – perhaps 100 to 1000 times the normal background rate of extinction.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Anthropogenic extinctions started as humans migrated out of Africa over 60,000 years ago.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Increases in global rates of extinction have been elevated above background rates since at least 1500, and appear to have accelerated in the 19th century and further since.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Rapid economic growth is considered a primary driver of the contemporary displacement and eradication of other species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Biodiversity loss happens when species disappear completely from Earth (extinction) or when there is a decrease or disappearance of species in a specific area.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Biodiversity loss means that there is a reduction in biological diversity in a given area.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The decrease can be temporary or permanent.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] It is temporary if the damage that led to the loss is reversible in time, for example through ecological restoration.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] If this is not possible, then the decrease is permanent.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The cause of most of the biodiversity loss is, generally speaking, human activities that push the planetary boundaries too far.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] These activities include habitat destruction (for example deforestation) and land use intensification (for example monoculture farming).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Further problem areas are air and water pollution (including nutrient pollution), over-exploitation, invasive species and climate change.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Many scientists, along with the *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services*, say that the main reason for biodiversity loss is a growing human population because this leads to human overpopulation and excessive consumption.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Others disagree, saying that loss of habitat is caused mainly by "the growth of commodities for export" and that population has very little to do with overall consumption.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] More important are wealth disparities between and within countries.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In any case, all contemporary biodiversity loss has been attributed to human activities.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Climate change is another threat to global biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] For example, coral reefs—which are biodiversity hotspots—will be lost by the year 2100 if global warming continues at the current rate.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Additionally, the change of temperatures are likely to increase fire activity driving events such as forest fires.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Still, it is the general habitat destruction (often for expansion of agriculture), not climate change, that is currently the bigger driver of biodiversity loss.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Invasive species and other disturbances have become more common in forests in the last several decades.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] These tend to be directly or indirectly connected to climate change and can cause a deterioration of forest ecosystems.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Studies of urban evolution give an indication of how species may respond to stressors such as temperature change and toxicity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Species display varying abilities to respond to altered environments through both phenotypic plasticity and genetic evolution.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Researchers have documented the movement of many species into regions formerly too cold for them, often at rates faster than initially expected.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Permanent changes in the distribution of organisms from human influence will become identifiable in the geologic record.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] This has occurred in part as a result of changing climate, but also in response to farming and fishing, and to the accidental introduction of non-native species to new areas through global travel.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The ecosystem of the entire Black Sea may have changed during the last 2000 years as a result of nutrient and silica input from eroding deforested lands along the Danube River.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Researchers have found that the growth of the human population and expansion of human activity has resulted in many species of animals that are normally active during the day, such as elephants, tigers and boars, becoming nocturnal to avoid contact with humans, who are largely diurnal.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] One geological symptom resulting from human activity is increasing atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) content.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] This signal in the Earth's climate system is especially significant because it is occurring much faster, and to a greater extent, than previously.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Most of this increase is due to the combustion of fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and gas.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Effects of climate change are well documented and growing for Earth's natural environment and human societies.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Changes to the climate system include an overall warming trend, changes to precipitation patterns, and more extreme weather.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] As the climate changes it impacts the natural environment with effects such as more intense forest fires, thawing permafrost, and desertification.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] These changes impact ecosystems and societies, and can become irreversible once tipping points are crossed.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Climate activists are engaged in a range of activities around the world that seek to ameliorate these issues or prevent them from happening.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The effects of climate change vary in timing and location.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Up until now the Arctic has warmed faster than most other regions due to climate change feedbacks.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Surface air temperatures over land have also increased at about twice the rate they do over the ocean, causing intense heat waves.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] These temperatures would stabilize if greenhouse gas emissions were brought under control.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Ice sheets and oceans absorb the vast majority of excess heat in the atmosphere, delaying effects there but causing them to accelerate and then continue after surface temperatures stabilize.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Sea level rise is a particular long term concern as a result.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The effects of ocean warming also include marine heatwaves, ocean stratification, deoxygenation, and changes to ocean currents.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The ocean is also acidifying as it absorbs carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Changes in drainage patterns traceable to human activity will persist over geologic time in large parts of the continents where the geologic regime is erosional.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] This involves, for example, the paths of roads and highways defined by their grading and drainage control.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Direct changes to the form of the Earth's surface by human activities (quarrying and landscaping, for example) also record human impacts.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] It has been suggested that the deposition of calthemite formations exemplify a natural process which has not previously occurred prior to the human modification of the Earth's surface, and which therefore represents a unique process of the Anthropocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Calthemite is a secondary deposit, derived from concrete, lime, mortar or other calcareous material *outside the cave environment*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Calthemites grow on or under man-made structures (including mines and tunnels) and mimic the shapes and forms of cave speleothems, such as stalactites, stalagmites, flowstone *etc*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Human activities, including deforestation and road construction, are believed to have elevated average total sediment fluxes across the Earth's surface.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] However, construction of dams on many rivers around the world means the rates of sediment deposition in any given place do not always appear to increase in the Anthropocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] For instance, many river deltas around the world are actually currently starved of sediment by such dams, and are subsiding and failing to keep up with sea level rise, rather than growing.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Increases in erosion due to farming and other operations will be reflected by changes in sediment composition and increases in deposition rates elsewhere.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In land areas with a depositional regime, engineered structures will tend to be buried and preserved, along with litter and debris.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Litter and debris thrown from boats or carried by rivers and creeks will accumulate in the marine environment, particularly in coastal areas, but also in mid-ocean garbage patches.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Such human-created artifacts preserved in stratigraphy are known as *technofossils*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Changes in biodiversity will also be reflected in the fossil record, as will species introductions.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Hence, landfills are important resources to find "technofossils".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In terms of trace elements, there are a range of distinct signatures left by modern societies.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] For example, in the Upper Fremont Glacier in Wyoming, there is a layer of chlorine present in ice cores from 1960's atomic weapon testing programs, as well as a layer of mercury associated with coal plants in the 1980s.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] From the late 1940s, nuclear tests have led to local nuclear fallout and severe contamination of test sites both on land and in the surrounding marine environment.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Some of the radionuclides that were released during the tests are 137Cs, 90Sr, 239Pu, 240Pu, 241Am, and 131I.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] These have been found to have had significant impact on the environment and on human beings.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In particular, 137Cs and 90Sr have been found to have been released into the marine environment and led to bioaccumulation over a period through food chain cycles.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The carbon isotope 14C, commonly released during nuclear tests, has also been found to be integrated into the atmospheric CO2, and infiltrating the biosphere, through ocean-atmosphere gas exchange.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Increase in thyroid cancer rates around the world is also surmised to be correlated with increasing proportions of the 131I radionuclide.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The highest global concentration of radionuclides was estimated to have been in 1965, one of the dates which has been proposed as a possible benchmark for the start of the formally defined Anthropocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Human burning of fossil fuels has also left distinctly elevated concentrations of black carbon, inorganic ash, and spherical carbonaceous particles in recent sediments across the world.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Concentrations of these components increases markedly and almost simultaneously around the world beginning around 1950.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] A marker that accounts for a substantial global impact of humans on the total environment, comparable in scale to those associated with significant perturbations of the geological past, is needed in place of minor changes in atmosphere composition.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] A range of markers characterizing the period have been identified, such as silicone or aluminium, but most prominently plastic, with plastic, reminiscent of archaeological ages like the Iron Age, marking an archaeological plastic age or the anthropocene even as a geological **plastic epoch**.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] A useful candidate for holding markers in the geologic time record is the pedosphere.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Soils retain information about their climatic and geochemical history with features lasting for centuries or millennia.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Human activity is now firmly established as the sixth factor of soil formation.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Human activity also affects pedogenesis indirectly by drift of eroded materials or pollutants.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Anthropogenic soils are those markedly affected by human activities, such as repeated ploughing, the addition of fertilisers, contamination, sealing, or enrichment with artefacts (in the World Reference Base for Soil Resources they are classified as Anthrosols and Technosols).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] An example from archaeology would be dark earth phenomena when long-term human habitation enriches the soil with black carbon.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Anthropogenic soils are recalcitrant repositories of artefacts and properties that testify to the dominance of the human impact, and hence appear to be reliable markers for the Anthropocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Some anthropogenic soils may be viewed as the 'golden spikes' of geologists (Global Boundary Stratotype Section and Point), which are locations where there are strata successions with clear evidences of a worldwide event, including the appearance of distinctive fossils.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Drilling for fossil fuels has also created holes and tubes which are expected to be detectable for millions of years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] An October 2020 study coordinated by University of Colorado at Boulder found that distinct physical, chemical and biological changes to Earth's rock layers began around the year 1950.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Humans have produced so many millions of tons of plastic each year since the early 1950s that microplastics are "forming a near-ubiquitous and unambiguous marker of Anthropocene".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The study highlights a strong correlation between global human population size and growth, global productivity and global energy use and that the "extraordinary outburst of consumption and productivity demonstrates how the Earth System has departed from its Holocene state since c.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Although the validity of *Anthropocene* as a scientific term remains disputed, its underlying premise, i.e., that humans have become a geological force, or rather, the dominant force shaping the Earth's climate, has found traction among academics and the public.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In an opinion piece for *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*, Rodolfo Dirzo, Gerardo Ceballos, and Paul R.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Ehrlich write that the term is "increasingly penetrating the lexicon of not only the academic socio-sphere, but also society more generally", and is now included as an entry in the Oxford English Dictionary.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The University of Cambridge, as another example, offers a degree in Anthropocene Studies.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In the public sphere, the term *Anthropocene* has become increasingly ubiquitous in activist, pundit, and political discourses.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Other scholars appreciate the way in which the term *Anthropocene* recognizes humanity as a geological force, but take issue with the indiscriminate way in which it does.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Not all humans are equally responsible for the climate crisis.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] To that end, scholars such as the feminist theorist Donna Haraway and sociologist Jason Moore, have suggested naming the Epoch instead as the *Capitalocene*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Such implies capitalism as the fundamental reason for the ecological crisis, rather than just humans in general.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] However, according to philosopher Steven Best, humans have created "hierarchical and growth-addicted societies" and have demonstrated "ecocidal proclivities" long before the emergence of capitalism.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Hartigan, Bould, and Haraway all critique what *Anthropocene* does as a term; however, Hartigan and Bould differ from Haraway in that they criticize the utility or validity of a geological framing of the climate crisis, whereas Haraway embraces it.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In addition to "Capitalocene," other terms have also been proposed by scholars to trace the roots of the Epoch to causes other than the human species broadly.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Janae Davis, for example, has suggested the "Plantationocene" as a more appropriate term to call attention to the role that plantation agriculture has played in the formation of the Epoch, alongside Kathryn Yusoff's argument that racism as a whole is foundational to the Epoch.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Other critiques of *Anthropocene* have focused on the genealogy of the concept.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] To that end, Todd makes the case that the concept of *Anthropocene* must be indigenized and decolonized if it is to become a vehicle of justice as opposed to white thought and domination.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Eco-philosopher David Abram, in a book chapter titled 'Interbreathing in the Humilocene', has proposed adoption of the term 'Humilocene' (the Epoch of Humility), which emphasizes an ethical imperative and ecocultural direction that human societies should take.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The term plays with the etymological roots of the term 'human', thus connecting it back with terms such as humility, humus (the soil), and even a corrective sense of humiliation that some human societies should feel given their collective destructive impact on the earth.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] William Ruddiman has argued that the Anthropocene began approximately 8,000 years ago with the development of farming and sedentary cultures.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] At that point, humans were dispersed across all continents except Antarctica, and the Neolithic Revolution was ongoing.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] During this period, humans developed agriculture and animal husbandry to supplement or replace hunter-gatherer subsistence.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Such innovations were followed by a wave of extinctions, beginning with large mammals and terrestrial birds.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] This wave was driven by both the direct activity of humans (e.g. hunting) and the indirect consequences of land-use change for agriculture.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Landscape-scale burning by prehistoric hunter-gathers may have been an additional early source of anthropogenic atmospheric carbon.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Ruddiman also claims that the greenhouse gas emissions in-part responsible for the Anthropocene began 8,000 years ago when ancient farmers cleared forests to grow crops.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Ruddiman's work has been challenged with data from an earlier interglaciation ("Stage 11", approximately 400,000 years ago) which suggests that 16,000 more years must elapse before the current Holocene interglaciation comes to an end, and thus the early anthropogenic hypothesis is invalid.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Also, the argument that "something" is needed to explain the differences in the Holocene is challenged by more recent research showing that all interglacials are different.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] This is due to the newfound globalism that humans participate in, as species traveling across the world to another region was not as easily possible in any point of time in history as it is today.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Curnutt in the year 2000 in *Ecology*, in a short list titled "A Guide to the Homogenocene", which reviewed *Alien species in North America and Hawaii: impacts on natural ecosystems* by George Cox.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Mann, in his acclaimed book *1493: Uncovering the New World Columbus Created*, gives a bird's-eye view of the mechanisms and ongoing implications of the homogenocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The concept of the Anthropocene has also been approached via humanities such as philosophy, literature and art.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In the scholarly world, it has been the subject of increasing attention through special journals, conferences, and disciplinary reports.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] The Anthropocene, its attendant timescale, and ecological implications prompt questions about death and the end of civilisation, memory and archives, the scope and methods of humanistic inquiry, and emotional responses to the "end of nature".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Some scholars have posited that the realities of the Anthropocene, including "human-induced biodiversity loss, exponential increases in per-capita resource consumption, and global climate change," have made the goal of environmental sustainability largely unattainable and obsolete.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Historians have actively engaged the Anthropocene.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In 2000, the same year that Paul Crutzen coined the term, world historian John McNeill published *Something New Under the Sun*, tracing the rise of human societies' unprecedented impact on the planet in the twentieth century.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] In 2001, historian of science Naomi Oreskes revealed the systematic efforts to undermine trust in climate change science and went on to detail the corporate interests delaying action on the environmental challenge.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Both McNeill and Oreskes became members of the Anthropocene Working Group because of their work correlating human activities and planetary transformation.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/anthropocene] Bridie Lonie has reflected that the Anthropocene has been a theme for art in New Zealand since the 1970s.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/aptian-extinction] The **Aptian extinction event** (**AEE**) was an extinction event that occurred during the Aptian stage of the early Cretaceous Period around 116 or 117 million years ago.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/aptian-extinction] It has sometimes been termed the **mid-Aptian extinction event**.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/aptian-extinction] It is classified as a minor extinction event, rather than a major event like the famous Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event that brought about the end of the Mesozoic Era.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/aptian-extinction] The Aptian event may have been causally connected with the Rahjamal Traps volcanism episode in the Bengal region of India, associated with the Kerguelen hotspot of volcanic activity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/aptian-extinction] During this time, India was located in the southern Indian Ocean and plate tectonics had not yet moved the Indian landmass into its present position.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/aptian-extinction] The Aptian event is most readily detected among marine deposits rather than terrestrial fossil deposits.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/aptian-extinction] From a palaeobotanical perspective, the Aptian Extinction Event is an episode of importance, deserving a higher status among other minor events.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/aptian-extinction] Stegosaurs such as Wuerhosaurus, among the last known stegosaurs a dinosaurs, went extinct along with surviving relatives of mammals such as the Tritylodonts.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] Extinctions are a normal part of the evolutionary process, and the background extinction rate is a measurement of "how often" they naturally occur.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] Normal extinction rates are often used as a comparison to present day extinction rates, to illustrate the higher frequency of extinction today than in all periods of non-extinction events before it.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] Background extinction rates have not remained constant, although changes are measured over geological time, covering millions of years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] There has been a decline in background extinction rates over the Phanerozoic eon, particularly from the middle of the Palaeozoic era, which has been attributed to increased oxygenation of the oceans.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] Background extinction rates are typically measured in order to give a specific classification to a species and this is obtained over a certain period of time.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] There are three different ways to calculate background extinction rate.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] The first is simply the number of species that normally go extinct over a given period of time.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] For example, at the background rate one species of bird will go extinct every estimated 400 years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] Another way the extinction rate can be given is in million species years (MSY).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] For example, there is approximately one extinction estimated per million species years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] From a purely mathematical standpoint this means that if there are a million species on the planet earth, one would go extinct every year, while if there was only one species it would go extinct in one million years, etc.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] The third way is in giving species survival rates over time.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] For example, given normal extinction rates species typically exist for 5–10 million years before going extinct.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/background-extinction-rate] Some groups' lifespan estimates by taxonomy are given below (Lawton & May 1995).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Since life began on Earth, six major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The Phanerozoic aeon (the last 540 million years) marked a rapid growth in biodiversity via the Cambrian explosion.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In this period, the majority of multicellular phyla first appeared.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The next 400 million years included repeated, massive biodiversity losses.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Those events have been classified as mass extinction events.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In the Carboniferous, rainforest collapse may have led to a great loss of plant and animal life.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The Permian–Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago, was the worst; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have led to an ongoing biodiversity loss and an accompanying loss of genetic diversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This process is often referred to as Holocene extinction, or the *sixth mass extinction*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] For example, it was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Destroying habitats for farming is a key reason why biodiversity is decreasing today.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This can be seen for example in the effects of climate change on biomes.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This anthropogenic extinction may have started toward the end of the Pleistocene, as some studies suggest that the megafaunal extinction event that took place around the end of the last ice age partly resulted from overhunting.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biologists most often define *biodiversity* as the "totality of genes, species and ecosystems of a region".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] (2011), there are approximately 8.7 million terrestrial species and 2.2 million oceanic species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The authors note that these estimates are strongest for eukaryotic organisms and likely represent the lower bound of prokaryotic diversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Since the rate of extinction has increased, many extant species may become extinct before they are described.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Not surprisingly, in the Animalia the most studied groups are birds and mammals, whereas fishes and arthropods are the least studied animal groups.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] During the last century, decreases in biodiversity have been increasingly observed.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] It was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Of these, about one eighth of known plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Estimates reach as high as 140,000 species per year (based on Species-area theory).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This figure indicates unsustainable ecological practices, because few species emerge each year.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The rate of species loss is greater now than at any time in human history, with extinctions occurring at rates hundreds of times higher than background extinction rates. and expected to still grow in the upcoming years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] As of 2012, some studies suggest that 25% of all mammal species could be extinct in 20 years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] According to a 2016 study by the World Wildlife Fund, population abundance among 3,706 monitored vertebrate species is exhibiting a persistent downward trend.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The *Living Planet Report 2014* claims that "the number of mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and fish across the globe is, on average, about half the size it was 40 years ago".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Of that number, 39% accounts for the terrestrial wildlife gone, 39% for the marine wildlife gone and 76% for the freshwater wildlife gone.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity took the biggest hit in Latin America, plummeting 83 percent.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] High-income countries showed a 10% increase in biodiversity, which was canceled out by a loss in low-income countries.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This is despite the fact that high-income countries use five times the ecological resources of low-income countries, which was explained as a result of a process whereby wealthy nations are outsourcing resource depletion to poorer nations, which are suffering the greatest ecosystem losses.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] A 2017 study published in *PLOS One* found that the biomass of insect life in Germany had declined by three-quarters in the last 25 years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Dave Goulson of Sussex University stated that their study suggested that humans "appear to be making vast tracts of land inhospitable to most forms of life, and are currently on course for ecological Armageddon.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In 2020 the World Wildlife Fund published a report saying that "biodiversity is being destroyed at a rate unprecedented in human history".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The report claims that 68% of the population of the examined species were destroyed in the years 1970 – 2016.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Of 70,000 monitored species, around 48% are experiencing population declines from human activity (in 2023), whereas only 3% have increasing populations.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Rates of decline in biodiversity in the current sixth mass extinction match or exceed rates of loss in the five previous mass extinction events in the fossil record.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity loss is in fact "one of the most critical manifestations of the Anthropocene" (since around the 1950s); the continued decline of biodiversity constitutes "an unprecedented threat" to the continued existence of human civilization.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The reduction is caused primarily by human impacts, particularly habitat destruction.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Since the Stone Age, species loss has accelerated above the average basal rate, driven by human activity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of species losses are at a rate 100–10,000 times as fast as is typical in the fossil record.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Loss of biodiversity results in the loss of natural capital that supplies ecosystem goods and services.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Species today are being wiped out at a rate 100 to 1,000 times higher than baseline, and the rate of extinctions is increasing.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This process destroys the resilience and adaptability of life on Earth.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In 2006, many species were formally classified as rare or endangered or threatened; moreover, scientists have estimated that millions more species are at risk which have not been formally recognized.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] About 40 percent of the 40,177 species assessed using the IUCN Red List criteria are now listed as threatened with extinction—a total of 16,119.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] As of late 2022 9251 species were considered part of the IUCN's critically endangered.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Numerous scientists and the IPBES *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* assert that human population growth and overconsumption are the primary factors in this decline.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] However, other scientists have criticized this finding and say that loss of habitat caused by "the growth of commodities for export" is the main driver.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] A 2025 study found that human activities are responsible for biodiversity loss across all species and ecosystems.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is an important driver of global biodiversity loss because of its impacts on ecosystems.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] At the same time, biodiversity and climate are closely interconnected, as biodiversity influences the mitigation and adaptation potential of ecosystems.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] For more information on these interactions, see the 'Regulating services' section below.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Other studies, however, have pointed out that habitat destruction for the expansion of agriculture and the overexploitation of wildlife are the more significant drivers of contemporary biodiversity loss, not climate change.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is not evenly distributed, rather it varies greatly across the globe as well as within regions and seasons.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Among other factors, the diversity of all living things (biota) depends on temperature, precipitation, altitude, soils, geography and the interactions between other species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The study of the spatial distribution of organisms, species and ecosystems, is the science of biogeography.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Diversity consistently measures higher in the tropics and in other localized regions such as the Cape Floristic Region and lower in polar regions generally.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Rain forests that have had wet climates for a long time, such as Yasuní National Park in Ecuador, have particularly high biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] There is local biodiversity, which directly impacts daily life, affecting the availability of fresh water, food choices, and fuel sources for humans.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Regional biodiversity includes habitats and ecosystems that synergizes and either overlaps or differs on a regional scale.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] National biodiversity within a country determines the ability for a country to thrive according to its habitats and ecosystems on a national scale.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Also, within a country, endangered species are initially supported on a national level then internationally.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Ecotourism may be utilized to support the economy and encourages tourists to continue to visit and support species and ecosystems they visit, while they enjoy the available amenities provided.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] International biodiversity impacts global livelihood, food systems, and health.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Problematic pollution, over consumption, and climate change can devastate international biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Nature-based solutions are a critical tool for a global resolution.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Many species are in danger of becoming extinct and need world leaders to be proactive with the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Terrestrial biodiversity is thought to be up to 25 times greater than ocean biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Forests harbour most of Earth's terrestrial biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The conservation of the world's biodiversity is thus utterly dependent on the way in which we interact with and use the world's forests.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] A new method used in 2011, put the total number of species on Earth at 8.7 million, of which 2.1 million were estimated to live in the ocean.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] However, this estimate seems to under-represent the diversity of microorganisms.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Forests provide habitats for 80 percent of amphibian species, 75 percent of bird species and 68 percent of mammal species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] About 60 percent of all vascular plants are found in tropical forests.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Mangroves provide breeding grounds and nurseries for numerous species of fish and shellfish and help trap sediments that might otherwise adversely affect seagrass beds and coral reefs, which are habitats for many more marine species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Forests span around 4 billion acres (nearly a third of the Earth's land mass) and are home to approximately 80% of the world's biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] About 1 billion hectares are covered by primary forests.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Over 700 million hectares of the world's woods are officially protected.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of forests varies considerably according to factors such as forest type, geography, climate and soils – in addition to human use.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Areas with dense human populations and intense agricultural land use, such as Europe, parts of Bangladesh, China, India and North America, are less intact in terms of their biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Northern Africa, southern Australia, coastal Brazil, Madagascar and South Africa, are also identified as areas with striking losses in biodiversity intactness.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] European forests in EU and non-EU nations comprise more than 30% of Europe's land mass (around 227 million hectares), representing an almost 10% growth since 1990.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Generally, there is an increase in biodiversity from the poles to the tropics.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Thus localities at lower latitudes have more species than localities at higher latitudes.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This is often referred to as the latitudinal gradient in species diversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Several ecological factors may contribute to the gradient, but the ultimate factor behind many of them is the greater mean temperature at the equator compared to that at the poles.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Even though terrestrial biodiversity declines from the equator to the poles, some studies claim that this characteristic is unverified in aquatic ecosystems, especially in marine ecosystems.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The latitudinal distribution of parasites does not appear to follow this rule.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Also, in terrestrial ecosystems the soil bacterial diversity has been shown to be highest in temperate climatic zones, and has been attributed to carbon inputs and habitat connectivity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In 2016, an alternative hypothesis ("the fractal biodiversity") was proposed to explain the biodiversity latitudinal gradient.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In this study, the species pool size and the fractal nature of ecosystems were combined to clarify some general patterns of this gradient.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This hypothesis considers temperature, moisture, and net primary production (NPP) as the main variables of an ecosystem niche and as the axis of the ecological hypervolume.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In this way, it is possible to build fractal hyper volumes, whose fractal dimension rises to three moving towards the equator.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] A biodiversity hotspot is a region with a high level of endemic species that have experienced great habitat loss.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The term hotspot was introduced in 1988 by Norman Myers.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] While hotspots are spread all over the world, the majority are forest areas and most are located in the tropics.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Brazil's Atlantic Forest is considered one such hotspot, containing roughly 20,000 plant species, 1,350 vertebrates and millions of insects, about half of which occur nowhere else.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The island of Madagascar and India are also particularly notable.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Colombia is characterized by high biodiversity, with the highest rate of species by area unit worldwide and it has the largest number of endemics (species that are not found naturally anywhere else) of any country.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] About 10% of the species of the Earth can be found in Colombia, including over 1,900 species of bird, more than in Europe and North America combined, Colombia has 10% of the world's mammals species, 14% of the amphibian species and 18% of the bird species of the world.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Madagascar dry deciduous forests and lowland rainforests possess a high ratio of endemism.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Since the island separated from mainland Africa 66 million years ago, many species and ecosystems have evolved independently.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Indonesia's 17,000 islands cover 735,355 square miles (1,904,560 km2) and contain 10% of the world's flowering plants, 12% of mammals and 17% of reptiles, amphibians and birds—along with nearly 240 million people.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Many regions of high biodiversity and/or endemism arise from specialized habitats which require unusual adaptations, for example, alpine environments in high mountains, or Northern European peat bogs.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Accurately measuring differences in biodiversity can be difficult.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Selection bias amongst researchers may contribute to biased empirical research for modern estimates of biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is the result of 3.5 billion years of evolution.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The origin of life has not been established by science, however, some evidence suggests that life may already have been well-established only a few hundred million years after the formation of the Earth.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Until approximately 2.5 billion years ago, all life consisted of microorganisms – archaea, bacteria, and single-celled protozoans and protists.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity grew fast during the Phanerozoic (the last 540 million years), especially during the so-called Cambrian explosion—a period during which nearly every phylum of multicellular organisms first appeared.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] However, recent studies suggest that this diversification had started earlier, at least in the Ediacaran, and that it continued in the Ordovician.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Over the next 400 million years or so, invertebrate diversity showed little overall trend and vertebrate diversity shows an overall exponential trend.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This dramatic rise in diversity was marked by periodic, massive losses of diversity classified as mass extinction events.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The worst was the Permian-Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Vertebrates took 30 million years to recover from this event.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The most recent major mass extinction event, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 66 million years ago.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This period has attracted more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs, which were represented by many lineages at the end of the Maastrichtian, just before that extinction event.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] However, many other taxa were affected by this crisis, which affected even marine taxa, such as ammonites, which also became extinct around that time.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of the past is called Paleobiodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The fossil record suggests that the last few million years featured the greatest biodiversity in history.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] However, not all scientists support this view, since there is uncertainty as to how strongly the fossil record is biased by the greater availability and preservation of recent geologic sections.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Some scientists believe that corrected for sampling artifacts, modern biodiversity may not be much different from biodiversity 300 million years ago, whereas others consider the fossil record reasonably reflective of the diversification of life.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of the present global macroscopic species diversity vary from 2 million to 100 million, with a best estimate of somewhere near 9 million, the vast majority arthropods.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Diversity appears to increase continually in the absence of natural selection.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The existence of a *global carrying capacity*, limiting the amount of life that can live at once, is debated, as is the question of whether such a limit would also cap the number of species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] While records of life in the sea show a logistic pattern of growth, life on land (insects, plants and tetrapods) shows an exponential rise in diversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] It also appears that the diversity continues to increase over time, especially after mass extinctions.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] On the other hand, changes through the Phanerozoic correlate much better with the hyperbolic model (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The latter models imply that changes in diversity are guided by a first-order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or a negative feedback arising from resource limitation.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Differences in the strength of the second-order feedback due to different intensities of interspecific competition might explain the faster rediversification of ammonoids in comparison to bivalves after the end-Permian extinction.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic pattern of the world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between the population size and the rate of technological growth.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be similarly accounted for by a feedback between diversity and community structure complexity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The similarity between the curves of biodiversity and human population probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of the hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Most biologists agree however that the period since human emergence is part of a new mass extinction, named the Holocene extinction event, caused primarily by the impact humans are having on the environment.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] It has been argued that the present rate of extinction is sufficient to eliminate most species on the planet Earth within 100 years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] New species are regularly discovered (on average between 5–10,000 new species each year, most of them insects) and many, though discovered, are not yet classified (estimates are that nearly 90% of all arthropods are not yet classified).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Most of the terrestrial diversity is found in tropical forests and in general, the land has more species than the ocean; some 8.7 million species may exist on Earth, of which some 2.1 million live in the ocean.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] It is estimated that 5 to 50 billion species have existed on the planet.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Assuming that there may be a maximum of about 50 million species currently alive, it stands to reason that greater than 99% of the planet's species went extinct prior to the evolution of humans.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Estimates on the number of Earth's current species range from 10 million to 14 million, of which about 1.2 million have been documented and over 86% have not yet been described.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] However, a May 2016 scientific report estimates that 1 trillion species are currently on Earth, with only one-thousandth of one percent described.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The total amount of related DNA base pairs on Earth is estimated at 5.0 × 1037 and weighs 50 billion tonnes.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In comparison, the total mass of the biosphere has been estimated to be as much as four trillion tons of carbon.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In July 2016, scientists reported identifying a set of 355 genes from the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all organisms living on Earth.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The age of Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The earliest undisputed evidence of life dates at least from 3.7 billion years ago, during the Eoarchean era after a geological crust started to solidify following the earlier molten Hadean eon.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] There are microbial mat fossils found in 3.48 billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Other early physical evidence of a biogenic substance is graphite in 3.7 billion-year-old meta-sedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] More recently, in 2015, "remains of biotic life" were found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] There have been many claims about biodiversity's effect on the ecosystem services, especially *provisioning* and *regulating services*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Some of those claims have been validated, some are incorrect and some lack enough evidence to draw definitive conclusions.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Experiments with controlled environments have shown that humans cannot easily build ecosystems to support human needs; for example insect pollination cannot be mimicked, though there have been attempts to create artificial pollinators using unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The economic activity of pollination alone represented between $2.1–14.6 billion in 2003.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Other sources have reported somewhat conflicting results and in 1997 Robert Costanza and his colleagues reported the estimated global value of ecosystem services (not captured in traditional markets) at an average of $33 trillion annually.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity plays a role in multiple ecological regulating services that strengthen the stability, functioning and adaptability of ecosystems.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] For example, plant species richness can increase functional diversity in many ecosystems.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Different plant organisms living together can perform complementary roles such as nutrient cycling and water regulation, which can contribute to the stabilisation of ecosystem processes under climate stress, a mechanism known as niche complementarity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This could include enhanced transpiration and soil moisture regulation, as more efficient water use can be promoted by the variety of different leaf traits and root depths, which in turn can reduce drought stress and mitigate heat impact.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is also associated with higher pathogen pressure on terrestrial and marine ecosystems.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In many ecosystems higher biodiversity could contribute to greater resilience to pests and diseases, as diversity in host traits and interactions can interrupt disease spread and reduce the severity of the outbreak.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In coastal ecosystems genetic diversity within a species can further enhance its adaptive capacity by providing a range of traits that support populations to persist under changing temperature and precipitation regimes.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Furthermore, in terrestrial ecosystems higher biodiversity can promote mutualistic interactions (like pollination or mycorrhizal networks), which can enhance nutrient uptake and support overall productivity and resilience.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The other category of agricultural diversity is called interspecific diversity and refers to the number and types of different species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Agricultural diversity can also be divided by whether it is 'planned' diversity or 'associated' diversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This is a functional classification that we impose and not an intrinsic feature of life or diversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Associated biodiversity can be damaging or beneficial.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The beneficial associated biodiversity include for instance wild pollinators such as wild bees and syrphid flies that pollinate crops and natural enemies and antagonists to pests and pathogens.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Beneficial associated biodiversity occurs abundantly in crop fields and provide multiple ecosystem services such as pest control, nutrient cycling and pollination that support crop production.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Although about 80 percent of humans' food supply comes from just 20 kinds of plants, humans use at least 40,000 species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Earth's surviving biodiversity provides resources for increasing the range of food and other products suitable for human use, although the present extinction rate shrinks that potential.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's relevance to human health is becoming an international political issue, as scientific evidence builds on the global health implications of biodiversity loss.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Some of the health issues influenced by biodiversity include dietary health and nutrition security, infectious disease, medical science and medicinal resources, social and psychological health.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is also known to have an important role in reducing disaster risk, including rising sea levels.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] For example, wetland ecosystems along coastal communities serve as excellent water filtration systems, storage, and ultimately create a buffer region between the ocean and mainland neighborhoods in order to prevent water reaching these communities under climate change pressures or storm surges.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Other examples of diverse species or organisms are present around the world, offering their resourceful utilities to provide protection of human survival.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity provides critical support for drug discovery and the availability of medicinal resources.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Only a tiny fraction of wild species has been investigated for medical potential.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This process of bioprospecting can increase biodiversity loss, as well as violating the laws of the communities and states from which the resources are taken.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] According to the Boston Consulting Group, in 2021, the economic value that biodiversity has on society comes down to four definable terms: regulation, culture, habitat, and provisioning.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] To sum these up in a relatively short manner, biodiversity helps maintain habitat and animal functions that provide considerable amounts of resources that benefit the economy.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's economic resources are worth at around $150 trillion annually which is roughly twice the world's GDP.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The loss of biodiversity is actually harming the GDP of the world by costing an estimated $5 trillion annually.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Business supply chains rely heavily on ecosystems remaining relatively maintained and nurtured.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] A disruption to these supply chains would negatively impact many businesses that would end up costing them more than what they are gaining.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Philosophically it could be argued that biodiversity has intrinsic aesthetic and spiritual value to mankind *in and of itself*.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This idea can be used as a counterweight to the notion that tropical forests and other ecological realms are only worthy of conservation because of the services they provide.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity also affords many non-material benefits including spiritual and aesthetic values, knowledge systems and education.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] A variety of objective means exist to empirically measure biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Each measure relates to a particular use of the data, and is likely to be associated with the variety of genes.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is commonly measured in terms of taxonomic richness of a geographic area over a time interval.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In order to calculate biodiversity, species evenness, species richness, and species diversity are to be obtained first.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] *Species evenness* is the relative number of individuals of each species in a given area.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] *Species richness* is the number of species present in a given area.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] *Species diversity* is the relationship between species evenness and species richness.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] There are many ways to measure biodiversity within a given ecosystem.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] However, the two most popular are Shannon-Weaver diversity index, commonly referred to as Shannon diversity index, and the other is Simpsons diversity index.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Although many scientists prefer to use Shannon's diversity index simply because it takes into account species richness.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Less than 1% of all species that have been described have been studied beyond noting their existence.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The vast majority of Earth's species are microbial.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Contemporary biodiversity physics is "firmly fixated on the visible [macroscopic] world".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] For example, microbial life is metabolically and environmentally more diverse than multicellular life (see e.g., extremophile).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] "On the tree of life, based on analyses of small-subunit ribosomal RNA, visible life consists of barely noticeable twigs.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The inverse relationship of size and population recurs higher on the evolutionary ladder—to a first approximation, all multicellular species on Earth are insects".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Insect extinction rates are high—supporting the Holocene extinction hypothesis.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity naturally varies due to seasonal shifts.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Spring's arrival enhances biodiversity as numerous species breed and feed, while winter's onset temporarily reduces it as some insects perish and migrating animals leave.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Additionally, the seasonal fluctuation in plant and invertebrate populations influences biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Barriers such as large rivers, seas, oceans, mountains and deserts encourage diversity by enabling independent evolution on either side of the barrier, via the process of allopatric speciation.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The term invasive species is applied to species that breach the natural barriers that would normally keep them constrained.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Without barriers, such species occupy new territory, often supplanting native species by occupying their niches, or by using resources that would normally sustain native species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Species are increasingly being moved by humans (on purpose and accidentally).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Some studies say that diverse ecosystems are more resilient and resist invasive plants and animals.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Many studies cite effects of invasive species on natives, but not extinctions.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Invasive species seem to increase local (alpha diversity) diversity, which decreases turnover of diversity (beta diversity).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Overall gamma diversity may be lowered because species are going extinct because of other causes, but even some of the most insidious invaders (e.g.: Dutch elm disease, emerald ash borer, chestnut blight in North America) have not caused their host species to become extinct.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Extirpation, population decline and homogenization of regional biodiversity are much more common.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have frequently been the cause of invasive species circumventing their barriers, by introducing them for food and other purposes.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Human activities therefore allow species to migrate to new areas (and thus become invasive) occurred on time scales much shorter than historically have been required for a species to extend its range.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] At present, several countries have already imported so many exotic species, particularly agricultural and ornamental plants, that their indigenous fauna/flora may be outnumbered.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] For example, the introduction of kudzu from Southeast Asia to Canada and the United States has threatened biodiversity in certain areas.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Another example are pines, which have invaded forests, shrublands and grasslands in the southern hemisphere.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Endemic species can be threatened with extinction through the process of genetic pollution, i.e. uncontrolled hybridization, introgression and genetic swamping.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Genetic pollution leads to homogenization or replacement of local genomes as a result of either a numerical and/or fitness advantage of an introduced species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Hybridization and introgression are side-effects of introduction and invasion.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] These phenomena can be especially detrimental to rare species that come into contact with more abundant ones.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The abundant species can interbreed with the rare species, swamping its gene pool.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] This problem is not always apparent from morphological (outward appearance) observations alone.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Some degree of gene flow is normal adaptation and not all gene and genotype constellations can be preserved.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] However, hybridization with or without introgression may, nevertheless, threaten a rare species' existence.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology matured in the mid-20th century as ecologists, naturalists and other scientists began to research and address issues pertaining to global biodiversity declines.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] The conservation ethic advocates management of natural resources for the purpose of sustaining biodiversity in species, ecosystems, the evolutionary process and human culture and society.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology is reforming around strategic plans to protect biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Preserving global biodiversity is a priority in strategic conservation plans that are designed to engage public policy and concerns affecting local, regional and global scales of communities, ecosystems and cultures.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Action plans identify ways of sustaining human well-being, employing natural capital, macroeconomic policies including economic incentives, and ecosystem services.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] In the EU Directive 1999/22/EC zoos are described as having a role in the preservation of the biodiversity of wildlife animals by conducting research or participation in breeding programs.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Removal of exotic species will allow the species that they have negatively impacted to recover their ecological niches.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Exotic species that have become pests can be identified taxonomically (e.g., with Digital Automated Identification SYstem (DAISY), using the barcode of life).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] Removal is practical only given large groups of individuals due to the economic cost.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p01] As sustainable populations of the remaining native species in an area become assured, "missing" species that are candidates for reintroduction can be identified using databases such as the *Encyclopedia of Life* and the Global Biodiversity Information Facility.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas, including forest reserves and biosphere reserves, serve many functions including for affording protection to wild animals and their habitat.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas have been set up all over the world with the specific aim of protecting and conserving plants and animals.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Some scientists have called on the global community to designate as protected areas of 30 percent of the planet by 2030, and 50 percent by 2050, in order to mitigate biodiversity loss from anthropogenic causes.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The target of protecting 30% of the area of the planet by the year 2030 (30 by 30) was adopted by almost 200 countries in the 2022 United Nations Biodiversity Conference.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] At the moment of adoption (December 2022) 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] In a study published 4 September 2020 in Science Advances researchers mapped out regions that can help meet critical conservation and climate goals.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas safeguard nature and cultural resources and contribute to livelihoods, particularly at local level.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] There are over 238 563 designated protected areas worldwide, equivalent to 14.9 percent of the earth's land surface, varying in their extension, level of protection, and type of management (IUCN, 2018).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of protected areas extend beyond their immediate environment and time.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] In addition to conserving nature, protected areas are crucial for securing the long-term delivery of ecosystem services.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] They provide numerous benefits including the conservation of genetic resources for food and agriculture, the provision of medicine and health benefits, the provision of water, recreation and tourism, and for acting as a buffer against disaster.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Increasingly, there is acknowledgement of the wider socioeconomic values of these natural ecosystems and of the ecosystem services they can provide.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] A national park is a large natural or near natural area set aside to protect large-scale ecological processes, which also provide a foundation for environmentally and culturally compatible, spiritual, scientific, educational, recreational and visitor opportunities.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] These areas are selected by governments or private organizations to protect natural biodiversity along with its underlying ecological structure and supporting environmental processes, and to promote education and recreation.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), and its World Commission on Protected Areas (WCPA), has defined "National Park" as its Category II type of protected areas.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Wildlife sanctuaries are areas of either shelter for animals who are unable to live in the wild on their own, or they are temporary rehabilitation centers for wildlife to improve in their overall health and wellbeing.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Both of these serve as places in which biodiversity can be preserved rather than harmed.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] According to an article published in the National Park Service website, national parks aim their resources at maintaining animal and habitat integrity through conservation and preservation of their ecosystems.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] This along with educating the general public on wildlife functions, the aim for an increase in biodiversity is one of many goals trying to be focused on through national parks.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Forest protected areas are a subset of all protected areas in which a significant portion of the area is forest.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] This may be the whole or only a part of the protected area.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Globally, 18 percent of the world's forest area, or more than 700 million hectares, fall within legally established protected areas such as national parks, conservation areas and game reserves.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] There is an estimated 726 million ha of forest in protected areas worldwide.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Of the six major world regions, South America has the highest share of forests in protected areas, 31 percent.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The forests play a vital role in harboring more than 45,000 floral and 81,000 faunal species of which 5150 floral and 1837 faunal species are endemic.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] In addition, there are 60,065 different tree species in the world.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Plant and animal species confined to a specific geographical area are called endemic species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] In forest reserves, rights to activities like hunting and grazing are sometimes given to communities living on the fringes of the forest, who sustain their livelihood partially or wholly from forest resources or products.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Approximately 50 million hectares (or 24%) of European forest land is protected for biodiversity and landscape protection.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Forests allocated for soil, water, and other ecosystem services encompass around 72 million hectares (32% of European forest area).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] It stated that "the state of nature has deteriorated at an unprecedented and accelerating rate".
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] To fix the problem, humanity will need a transformative change, including sustainable agriculture, reductions in consumption and waste, fishing quotas and collaborative water management.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive is playing a role in mainstreaming the goals of the Global Biodiversity Framework (GBF) for biodiversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The aim of mainstreaming is to embed biodiversity considerations into public and private practice to conserve and sustainably use biodiversity on global and local levels.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive refers to the societal goal to halt and reverse biodiversity loss, measured from a baseline of 2020 levels, and to achieve full so-called "nature recovery" by 2050.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Citizen science, also known as public participation in scientific research, has been widely used in environmental sciences and is particularly popular in a biodiversity-related context.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] It has been used to enable scientists to involve the general public in biodiversity research, thereby enabling the scientists to collect data that they would otherwise not have been able to obtain.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Volunteer observers have made significant contributions to on-the-ground knowledge about biodiversity, and recent improvements in technology have helped increase the flow and quality of occurrences from citizen sources.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] A 2016 study published in Biological Conservation registers the massive contributions that citizen scientists already make to data mediated by the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Despite some limitations of the dataset-level analysis, it is clear that nearly half of all occurrence records shared through the GBIF network come from datasets with significant volunteer contributions.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Recording and sharing observations are enabled by several global-scale platforms, including iNaturalist and eBird.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Global agreements such as the Convention on Biological Diversity, give "sovereign national rights over biological resources" (not property).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The agreements commit countries to "conserve biodiversity", "develop resources for sustainability" and "share the benefits" resulting from their use.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Biodiverse countries that allow bioprospecting or collection of natural products, expect a share of the benefits rather than allowing the individual or institution that discovers/exploits the resource to capture them privately.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Bioprospecting can become a type of biopiracy when such principles are not respected.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Sovereignty principles can rely upon what is better known as Access and Benefit Sharing Agreements (ABAs).
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The Convention on Biodiversity implies informed consent between the source country and the collector, to establish which resource will be used and for what and to settle on a fair agreement on benefit sharing.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The agreement includes also recovering 30% of earth degraded ecosystems and increasing funding for biodiversity issues.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] In May 2020, the European Union published its Biodiversity Strategy for 2030.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The biodiversity strategy is an essential part of the climate change mitigation strategy of the European Union.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] From the 25% of the European budget that will go to fight climate change, large part will go to restore biodiversity and nature based solutions.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Approximately half of the global GDP depend on nature.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] In Europe many parts of the economy that generate trillions of euros per year depend on nature.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of Natura 2000 alone in Europe are €200 – €300 billion per year.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Uniform approval for use of biodiversity as a legal standard has not been achieved, however.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] Bosselman argues that biodiversity should not be used as a legal standard, claiming that the remaining areas of scientific uncertainty cause unacceptable administrative waste and increase litigation without promoting preservation goals.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] India passed the Biological Diversity Act in 2002 for the conservation of biological diversity in India.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/biodiversity-p02] The Act also provides mechanisms for equitable sharing of benefits from the use of traditional biological resources and knowledge.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] A species that is **extinct in the wild** (**EW**) is one that has been categorized by the International Union for Conservation of Nature as only consisting of living members kept in captivity or as a naturalized population outside its historic range.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Classification requires exhaustive surveys conducted within the species' known habitat with consideration given to seasonality, time of day, and life cycle.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Once a species is classified as EW, the only way for it to be downgraded is through reintroduction.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] An example is the *Brugmansia* genus, where all seven species are widely cultivated, but none are found in the wild.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Reintroduction is the deliberate release of individuals into the wild, from captivity or from other areas where the species survives.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] However, it may be difficult to reintroduce EW species into the wild, even if their natural habitats were restored, because survival techniques, which are often passed from parents to offspring during parenting, may have been lost.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Reintroduction efforts, also referred to as translocation, are complex and a common source of complication is how animals behave upon release.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Climate suitability has been shown to influence reintroduction outcomes as well.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Though many efforts translocate populations to historic ranges, climate change may be causing those previously inhabited areas to no longer be suitable for the species.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] The Przewalski's horse was downgraded from EW to Endangered in 2011 after decades of reintroduction efforts.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] In China, they are still classified as EW since they are given supplemental feed over the winter to aid survival.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Of the 2500 living, about 1360 are in the wild, and all 2500 are descended from 12 wild-caught ancestors, causing an inbreeding depression that contributes to factors, such as shorter lifespans and high mortality, that impede conservation.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Northern white rhinos have been extinct in the wild since 2007, and only two females remain in captivity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] The San Diego Zoo Global is planning to save the species by using living cells from 12 rhinos that have been cryopreserved, turning them into stem cell lines, using in vitro fertilization to create embryos, and then having Southern white rhinos serve as surrogates.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Currently, there have been no successful embryo transfers in rhinos.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] It is estimated to take at least 40 years for the target of 25–40 northern white rhinos to be reached.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Some people critique efforts to save species with such small populations due to the possibility of inbreeding as it can reduce the population growth rate.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Small effective population sizes are another critique.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Effective population size is a measurement of the loss of genetic diversity.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Multiple populations have been found to have an effective population size below conservation goals.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Additionally, monitoring effective population size and using it to aid estimations of the success of conservation efforts has been shown to provide a better overview of determining population trends when compared to population size.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] The IUCN developed a system of classifying species recovery efforts in 2012 entitled the Green Status.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] The species recovery score is a 0%–100% scale, with 0% being the species is extinct or extinct in the wild and 100% being fully recovered.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] In addition, the Green Status also classifies previous and future conservation impacts with the Green Scores of Conservation Dependency, Conservation Gain, Conservation Legacy, and Recovery Potential.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] For a species to receive a score of 100% and be considered fully recovered, three requirements must be met: the species must be present in all areas of both its current and historical range, it is viable in all areas of the range, and performs its ecological niche across the full range.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Given the lofty standards, many species are not expected to meet the criteria and it is not a goal of this system.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Land use changes have cumulated in many species losing habitat.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Green Scores are snapshots in time to assess a species' current status and how conservation efforts have influenced their status.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] It is also predictive as it can project how the status would change if conservation efforts ceased or continued.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Conservation Legacy assess how previous conservation work has changed or maintained a species' status.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] The score ranges from high to low with low meaning conservation efforts were ineffective or did not occur.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Conservation Dependency is the estimate of a species' status in 10 years if conservation efforts halted.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] High dependency means the species would have a lower status and low dependency equates to the status not changing.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] It projects a species' status in 10 years if conservation efforts continue.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Both dependence and gain are considered short-term measures.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] The long-term measure is Recovery Potential, which is how much of the range is estimated to be able to house ecologically functional populations.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] The Pinta Island tortoise (*Geochelone nigra abingdoni*) had only one living individual, named Lonesome George, until his death in June 2012.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] The tortoise was believed to be extinct in the mid-20th century, until Hungarian malacologist József Vágvölgyi spotted Lonesome George on the Galapagos island of Pinta on 1 December 1971.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] Since then, Lonesome George has been a powerful symbol for conservation efforts in general and for the Galapagos Islands in particular.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] With his death on 24 June 2012, the subspecies is again believed to be extinct.
[src:extinct-in-the-wild/extinct-in-the-wild] With the discovery of 17 hybrid Pinta tortoises located at nearby Wolf Volcano, a plan has been made to attempt to breed the subspecies back into a pure state.
